<h2>How Pour Over Works</h2>

<p>
  Pour over (percolation) brewing works by pouring water over a bed of coffee grounds and letting gravity pull it through. Unlike immersion methods (such as French press), the water is <strong>constantly fresh as it contacts the coffee</strong>. As water passes through the grounds and picks up dissolved compounds, the concentration gradient between grounds and water is maintained — driving continuous extraction.
</p>

<p>
  The most critical variable in pour over is the relationship between <strong>flow rate and contact time</strong>. Longer contact means higher extraction; faster flow means lower extraction. Flow rate is determined by dripper shape, number of holes, and filter material. Ideal pour over achieves even saturation across the entire coffee bed — avoiding "channeling," where water finds a path of least resistance and causes uneven extraction (over-extracted in channels, under-extracted elsewhere).
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Pour Over Fundamentals</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>Brew ratio:</strong> 1:15–1:17 (1g coffee to 15–17g water)<br />
    <strong>Water temperature:</strong> 85–96°C (lower for dark roasts, higher for light)<br />
    <strong>Grind size:</strong> Medium-fine to medium (varies by dripper)<br />
    <strong>Total brew time:</strong> 2:30–4:00 minutes<br />
    <strong>Target TDS:</strong> 1.2–1.45% / Extraction yield: 18–22%
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Dripper Shape Comparison</h2>

<p>
  The three main dripper shapes — cone, trapezoid, and flat-bottom — each produce different results due to how they distribute water through the coffee bed.
</p>

